## Steps to Reproduce

1. Define an explicitly-typed local/field/property S with type `T[]`, where `T` can be any initializable type with an object initializer
2. Define a type that can be initialized with an object initializer
3. Assign a collection expression to S, and initialize its elements with target-typed constructors (`new()`)
4. Attempt to fill the object within the object initializer

Test code:

```csharp
public static class TestClass
{
    private static SimpleRange[] _ranges;

    public static void Method()
    {
        _ranges =
        [
            new()
            {
                Start = 1,
                End = 3,
            },
        ];
    }
}

public struct SimpleRange
{
    public int Start;
    public int End { get; set; }
};
```

## Expected Behavior

The suggestions include the available symbols for assignment (`Start` and `End` in the above example).

## Actual Behavior

The suggestions do not include any of the type's members.
Note that the suggestions properly appear for `List<T>`, like if `_ranges` is of type `List<SimpleRange>`.

